      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, so my tomato plants are looking kind of weird. The leaves on the bottom of the plants are turning all yellow, but the new growth at the top looks fine. Do you know what might be going on with them? I'm worried I'm doing something wrong with the soil.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellow leaves on tomato plants can be a bit of a mystery, but I'm here to help you dig into the issue. It's possible that your plants are experiencing a bit of a \"garden goblin\" problem, where the lower leaves are getting too much water and nutrients, causing them to rot and turn yellow. You might be overwatering or fertilizing, which is a common mistake that can lead to this issue. Think of it like a goblin's lair - too much treasure can be a curse, and too much water can be a recipe for disaster. \n\nHowever, it's also possible that the issue is related to the soil itself. Tomatoes prefer well-draining, fertile soil with a pH between 6.0 and 6.8. If your soil is too dense or lacking in nutrients, it could be causing the lower leaves to turn yellow. You might need to add some organic matter like compost or manure to give your soil a boost. \n\nTo diagnose the issue, take a closer look at your plants and see if you can spot any other signs of stress or disease. Check for pests, like aphids or whiteflies, which can also cause yellowing leaves. And remember, a little",
