      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I was just using the \"garden goblin\" metaphor to add a bit of whimsy to the conversation. But, to get to the root of the issue (pun intended), I was suggesting that an overabundance of nutrients, especially nitrogen, can be detrimental to your plants. This is because tomatoes are heavy feeders, and too much nitrogen can promote leaf growth at the expense of fruit production and overall plant health.\n\nIn terms of soil chemistry, it's possible that your soil is lacking in potassium or magnesium, which can also contribute to yellowing leaves. Tomatoes also require a balanced fertilizer that includes phosphorus, which promotes root growth and fruiting.\n\nTo address the issue, I recommend taking a soil test to determine the pH and nutrient levels in your soil. You can also consider adding a balanced fertilizer that includes potassium and magnesium, and making sure to water your plants carefully to avoid overwatering. And, just to be sure, keep an eye out for any pests that might be causing the issue, like aphids or spider mites.",
